{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5b8fd4e9-16b1-453f-a76f-f877503bb5e4","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process ID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** by opening `trace.nettrace` in Visual Studio, [PerfView](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview), or convert to speedscope format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or [dotnet-monitor](https://github.com/dotnet/dotnet-monitor) as a sidecar for on-demand collection via HTTP API.\n- For **production-safe, low-overhead** tracing, prefer `dotnet-trace` over `perf` — it uses EventPipe which is designed for production use.\n- Add `--buffersize 256` if you're seeing dropped events.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c9ac2b84-6b27-45e4-b32d-a58209bdaaea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":465,"requestId":"DA1A:1B074D:2230F5F:25C8DA1:6A03D4D1"},"id":"4371b558-2891-4116-a868-f5c7a6c3607f","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:33:15.949Z","parentId":"14603822-7e27-4c3a-9193-546c8f0bd565"}
